  &lt;p id="pi2YNy"&gt;This summer, Ford decided to spin out its budding self-driving car program &lt;a href="https://media.ford.com/content/fordmedia/fna/us/en/news/2018/07/24/ford-creates-ford-autonomous-vehicles-llc.html"&gt;into its own business&lt;/a&gt;. During a recent interview on&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://pca.st/vergecast"&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Vergecast&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, Ford AV CEO Sherif Marakby shared his vision for the automaker’s autonomous push, including a few new details about the status of the company’s first dedicated self-driving car, which is due out in 2021. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="afrwVO"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p id="aPcrVu"&gt;That car is supposed to be the linchpin of a fully autonomous shuttle and cargo service that will launch the same year, and it’s already past the design and clay modeling phase, Marakby said. And it’s most likely going to resemble something more like an SUV than the Fusion sedans Ford is currently using to test its self-driving technology in cities like Miami and Pittsburgh. &lt;/p&gt;
